Nigeria raked in $663.24 million making her to be the country with the highest amount of venture capital money inflows in 2019 according to the African Venture Capital Report 2019, carried out by WeeTracker. According to the report, Kenya had a super growth year netting 283.64 per cent growth over the previous year’s funding amount. South Africa took the third position in the top three countries as per funding amount. The report showed the analyses of 20 industries, 54 countries and over 20 deal types with a comparison to 2018 numbers. It also takes into consideration feedback and queries raised by several readers of our previous reports. According to the report, Fintech, which is on a growth path for the fifth year in a row securing $678.73 million, witnessed a spectacular growth of 138.48 per cent over the previous year. The ecosystem appears solid for the companies to set their footing as evident from the rise in seed and Series A rounds which were the most preferred form of deal closures for the investors. The local investors did not stay behind in loosening their purse string and did not fail to surprise the African startup ecosystem with bigger rounds. It said 24 Mergers and Acquisition deals took place during 2019 which was a 50 per cent growth over 2018 numbers. Meanwhile, with the current market climate, the venture capital market in 2020 is expected to remain robust, particularly in areas such as fintech, logistics, on-demand services and Agritech. The report further show that the African venture investments broke all the previous records to register $1.340 billion in investments through 427 deals in equity and debt financing in 2019. The enablers of the ecosystem continued to show their commitment towards hacking the growth opportunities on the continent, which are as diverse as its challenges. 